Chest X-Ray Image Classification for Pneumonia Detection using Convolutional Neural Network

I. Business Problem

Problem Statement

Pneumonia remains a leading cause of mortality among young children in developing countries and elderly populations in developed regions (Ruuskanen et al., 2011). Although, despite the severity and commonality of this disease, it is very much treatable with today's technology. Treatment is significantly more effective when detected earlier but manual diagnosis even by seasoned doctors can take time and prone to human error, especially during busy healthcare settings. This is why it is essential to have the capability to detect this disease faster, earlier, and more accurately.

Data Collection

For this assessment, we will use the Kaggle Chest X-Ray Pneumonia Dataset, which contains labeled X-ray images of healthy patients and patients with pneumonia. Images includes variations in gender, age, and imaging conditions which reflects real-world scenarios.

Machine Learning Task

Given the problem statement and nature of our dataset, we can formulate this Machine Learning task as a Binary Image Classification Problem. The input to the model is a chest X-ray image, and the output is a probability score indicating whether the image corresponds to a Normal or Pneumonia case.

Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) are well suited for this task due to their ability to automatically learn hierarchical spatial features such as lung opacity, texture patterns, and structural abnormalities directly from image data.

Benefits

  • Faster and more accurate identification of pneumonia cases which supports early clinical intervention
  • Improves consistency of diagnosis by reducing human error
  • Reduce workload for doctors/radiologists through automated screening
  • Future studies can scale the framework of this study to detect other chest conditions/diseases

The dataset we will be using comes from the Kaggle Chest X-Ray Pneumonia Dataset. It contains grayscale images and is pre-organized into labels of patients with and without pneumonia.

def show_sample_images(cls, n=3):
    img_paths = glob(f"{base_dir}/train/{cls}/*.jpeg")
    sample_paths = np.random.choice(img_paths, n, replace=False)

    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))
    for i, img_path in enumerate(sample_paths):
        img = plt.imread(img_path)
        plt.subplot(1, n, i+1)
        plt.imshow(img, cmap="gray")
        plt.title(f"{cls} Example")
        plt.axis("off")
    plt.suptitle(f"Sample {cls} Images (TRAIN)")
    plt.show()

EDA 3: Inconsistent image size and quality

Takeaways

  1. The original validation set is too small for effective model tuning; therefore, training and validation data are re-split using a stratified approach.
  2. Significant class imbalance exists in the training data, which is addressed using class weights and stratified split. Augmentation techniques like SMOTE is not advised when working with image data
  3. Images vary in resolution and quality. Meaning we have to resize and normalize the images in our dataset to have a uniform consistent inputs.

IV. Data Preprocessing

To solve EDA 1, we merge train and val folders so that we can split again later into proper 80/20 split

In[5]:
# Merge Train and Val Folders
train_dir = base_dir / "train"
val_dir   = base_dir / "val"

for cls in ["NORMAL", "PNEUMONIA"]:
    src_dir = val_dir / cls
    dst_dir = train_dir / cls

    for img_file in src_dir.glob("*"):
        dst_file = dst_dir / img_file.name

        counter = 1
        while dst_file.exists():
            dst_file = dst_dir / f"{img_file.stem}_{counter}{img_file.suffix}"
            counter += 1
        shutil.move(str(img_file), str(dst_file))

# Display
print("Merged validation images into the training folder.")

for cls in ["NORMAL", "PNEUMONIA"]:
    filenames = [f.name for f in (train_dir / cls).glob("*")]
    duplicates = pd.Series(filenames).duplicated().sum()
    print(f"Class {cls} - duplicates after merge: {duplicates}")

for cls in ["NORMAL", "PNEUMONIA"]:
    total = len(list((train_dir / cls).glob("*")))
    print(f"Class {cls} - total images after merge: {total}")

We can solve EDA 2 and 3, and split our merged training data using ImageDataGenerator from Keras.

Using ImageDataGenerator we will resize all images to 224x224 pixels and normalize to [0,1] range. Data augmentation techniques will be applied to the training set to improve generalization, while the validation and test set will only be rescaled.

In[6]:

Given the severity of our class imbalance from EDA 1, Data augmentation alone may not fully solve our this problem.

Class weights - will also be used during our training to help address imbalance. This means higher class weight will be assigned to the minority class (NORMAL) to penalize misclassification more heavily, encouraging the model to learn discriminative features for underrepresented samples

In[7]:
#Class Weights

from sklearn.utils.class_weight import compute_class_weight

classes = train_data.classes
class_weights_array = compute_class_weight(
    class_weight='balanced',
    classes=np.unique(classes),
    y=classes
)
class_weights = {i: class_weights_array[i] for i in range(len(class_weights_array))}

#Display
print("Class weights:", class_weights)

# Processed Data Check

def get_counts(generator):
    unique, counts = np.unique(generator.classes, return_counts=True)
    class_mapping = {v: k for k, v in generator.class_indices.items()}
    return {class_mapping[u]: c for u, c in zip(unique, counts)}


train_counts = get_counts(train_data)
val_counts   = get_counts(val_data)
test_counts  = get_counts(test_data)

# Display

V. Data Modelling

Baseline CNN

A standard CNN architecture comprising of:

  • 3 Convolution Blocks with maxpooling(2x2), 3x3 kernels, ReLU as the activation function, and progressively increasing filters
  • Flatten to convert learned feature maps into a vector which will be passed to a dense layer
  • Dropout for regularization which is initially set at 0.5 but will be optimized later on.
  • Dense output layer with sigmoid activation function to output probabilities from [0,1] since we are working on a binary classification problem.

Three convolutional blocks provides sufficient capacity to learn hierarchical features from X-ray images without a high risk of overfitting given the size of the dataset.

Optimizer = Adam optimizer will be used for its adaptive learning rate, fast convergence, and widespread usage in medical image classification. The initial learning rate of 1e-3 was selected as a starting point for experimentation..

Early Stopping will be used for the entire process so as to not remove the need to optimize epoch (will set initial_epoch at 25).

Checkpoints to monitor training.

In[]:
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, MaxPooling2D, Flatten, Dense, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping, ModelCheckpoint

# Baseline CNN Architecture
def build_baseline_cnn(input_shape=(224,224,3)):
    model = Sequential([
        Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu', input_shape=input_shape),
        MaxPooling2D(2,2),

        Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu'),
        MaxPooling2D(2,2),

        Conv2D(128, (3,3), activation='relu'),
        MaxPooling2D(2,2),

        Flatten(),
        Dense(128, activation='relu'),
        Dropout(0.5),
        Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
    ])
    return model

baseline_cnn = build_baseline_cnn()
baseline_cnn.compile(
    optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=1e-3),
    loss='binary_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

baseline_cnn.summary()

# Callbacks
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(
    monitor='val_loss',
    patience=5,
    restore_best_weights=True
)

checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(
    "baseline_cnn_best.keras",
    monitor='val_loss',
    save_best_only=True,
    verbose=1
)

# Train Model
history_baseline = baseline_cnn.fit(
    train_data,
    validation_data=val_data,
    epochs=25,
    class_weight=class_weights,
    callbacks=[early_stopping, checkpoint]
)

Experimentation

From our baseline CNN model we will conduct 'experiments' by sequentially adjusting the model's architecture and hyperparameters one-by-one while recording and comparing the runtime/speed and val_accuracy of each step to come up with our 'best model'

Structure of the Experiments:

  • Compare with Transfer Learning (Resnet50)
  • Architecture - Ensure we get the right and enough network capacity to learn features
  • Regularization - To Control Overfitting
  • Optimization - Hyperparameter Tuning

Despite several experimentations, the final model was just the baseline model with batch normalization, and learning rate scheduler and class weights applied.

Sometimes, the simplier model is just better and more practical to use

Final Model

In[]:
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras import layers, models, optimizers, callbacks

# Configurations
IMG_SIZE = (224, 224)
LEARNING_RATE = 1e-3
EPOCHS = 25
MODEL_PATH = "final_cnn_best.keras"

# Architecture
final_cnn = models.Sequential([
    layers.Input(shape=(*IMG_SIZE, 3)),

    layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
    layers.BatchNormalization(),
    layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)),

    layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
    layers.BatchNormalization(),
    layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)),

    layers.Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
    layers.BatchNormalization(),
    layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)),

    layers.Flatten(),
    layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    layers.Dropout(0.5),

    layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])

# Compile
final_cnn.compile(
    optimizer=optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=LEARNING_RATE),
    loss='binary_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

final_cnn.summary()

# Callbacks
early_stopping = callbacks.EarlyStopping(
    monitor='val_loss',
    patience=5,
    restore_best_weights=True
)

model_checkpoint = callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(
    MODEL_PATH,
    monitor='val_loss',
    save_best_only=True
)

lr_scheduler = callbacks.ReduceLROnPlateau(
    monitor='val_loss',
    factor=0.3,
    patience=3,
    min_lr=1e-6
)

# Train
history_final = final_cnn.fit(
    train_data,
    validation_data=val_data,
    epochs=EPOCHS,
    class_weight=class_weights,
    callbacks=[early_stopping, model_checkpoint, lr_scheduler]
)

The final model was selected based on the best balance between validation accuracy, training stability, and computational efficiency.

VI. Evaluation

Threshold adjustment

Pneumonia detection is a screening task, this missing a case (false negative) is clinically more dangerous, whereas a false positive is less harmful because these cases could still be caught with additional testing. Therefore, recall is generally considered more critical than precision in most medical application.

To prioritize recall, the classification threshold will be adjusted to 0.35. This is consistent with medical ML literature and ensures that missed pneumonia cases are minimized while keeping false positives at an acceptable level.

VII. Final Discussion

Model Strengths

  • High Recall - The final CNN model achieved a high recall of 0.9897 at a threshold of 0.35 which ensures almost all pneumonia cases are detected. This is critical in clinical screening.

  • Simple and Efficient Architecture - The baseline CNN + batch normalization + dropout + class weights + learning rate scheduler. This architecture is computationally efficienct and good predictive performance.

  • Robustness to Imbalanced Data - Stratified splitting and use of class weights effectively mitigated our dataset imbalance between pneumonia and normal cases.

Limitations

  • Dataset Limitation - The Kaggle Chest X-Ray dataset may not fully capture variations across populations, imaging equipment, or disease severity.

  • Explanabality and Interpretability - CNNs are inherently complex models which may be difficult to understand and explain to healthcare professionals. This can be adressed visual explanations like grad-cam but was not able to implement it in this pipeline due to GPU limits. Good to implement for future improvements

  • False Positives - Relatively high false positive meaning some normal cases are misclassified as pneumonia which may increase unnecessary follow-up tests. But clinically, this is more acceptable than missing a pneumonia case.

  • Binary classification (not multiclass) - The model currently only differentiates pneumonia vs normal and does not classify other chest conditions.

Business Implications

From the problem statement, we state that "it is essential to have the capability to detect this (pneumonia) disease faster, earlier, and more accurately." This pipeline/model solves that by:

  • Faster Diagnosis - Deploying this model can reduce the time required for manual chest X-ray review, increasing productivity of radiologists/clinicians.

  • Early Intervention - High recall ensures pneumonia cases are flagged promptly, and the model can also be used to detect preliminary symptoms of pneumonia.

  • Minimize human-error - Manually checking x-ray results of several patients under busy environment in hospitals may cause mistakes by clinicians. This model can consistently discriminate patients with pneumonia which can help alleviate that problem.

  • Resource Optimization - Automating the initial screening process reduces workload and operational costs without compromising safety.

Data-driven recommendations

  • Model-Assisted Screening - Using this CNN model as an intitial screening for X-rays to flag probable pneumonia cases which will then be reviewed by radiologist.

  • Improve Model Performance - Collect real-world feedback and data to update the model regularly, improving robustness across different features, demographics, and chest pathologies.

Will you deploy your model?

Yes, because:

  • The model is lightweight and fast enough to be integrated into hospital softwares/systems

  • Can be used as a triage tool to flag suspected pneumonia cases for radiologist review later (not to replace doctor diagnosis) given the model's good performance in discriminating between patients with/without pneumonia

  • Incorporate cloud infrastructures and dashboards to track model performance and patient conditions over time.
